Definition: Any tract of land or building used for agricultural purposes, such as for raising crops and livestock.
A person who works the land or who keeps livestock, especially on a farm.
Wind winnowing is an agricultural method developed by ancient cultures for separating grain from chaff.
A plant-eating insect with long back legs that can jump very high and makes a sharp high noise using its back legs or wings.
An aquatic bird of the family Anatidae, having a flat bill and webbed feet.

Any living organism characterized by voluntary movement, the possession of cells with noncellulose cell walls and specialized sense organs enabling rapid response to stimuli, and the ingestion of complex organic substances such as plants and other animals.
A generally tubular invertebrate of the annelid phylum.
Any of the membranous-winged insects which compose the superfamily Apoidea in the order Hymenoptera characterized by a hairy body and by sucking and chewing mouthparts.

Any insectivorous anuran amphibian of the family Ranidae, such as Rana temporaria of Europe, having a short squat tailless body with a moist smooth skin and very long hind legs specialized for hopping.
Any predatory silk-producing arachnid of the order Araneae, having four pairs of legs and a rounded unsegmented body consisting of abdomen and cephalothorax.
Any of the bipedal, warm-blooded vertebrates that lay eggs having wings which, for most species, enables them to fly.
The most primitive of the living winged insects.
Domesticated bovine animals, including cows, steers and bulls, raised and bred on a ranch or farm.
A common four-legged animal, especially kept by people as a pet or to hunt or guard things.
A large wild canid (Canidae), closely related to the dog.
Refers to *genus canis*, a genus containing seven to ten extant species, including wolves, domestic dogs, coyotes, and jackals.
A common four-legged animal (Capra) that is related to sheep and bred by humans for its coat and milk.
The common name for 41 species of even-toed ungulates that compose the family Cervidae in the order Artiodactyla; males have antlers.
Large marine mammals of the order Cetacea; the body is streamlined, the broad flat tail is used for propulsion, and the limbs are balancing structures.
A bird, usually black, of the genus Corvus, having a strong conical beak, with projecting bristles; it has a harsh, croaking call.
A small flying insect (of the family Culicidae) known for biting and sucking blood.
A common insect; any species of insect of the order Diptera.
A mythical creature typically depicted as a large horned serpent (Asia) or a winged, fire-breathing reptile (Europe), with magical or spiritual qualities.
A mammal of the order Proboscidea, having a trunk, and two large ivory tusks jutting from the upper jaw. Elephants are the largest land animals now existing.
A domesticated animal, Equus asinus.
A large animal with four legs of the Equus caballus species which people ride on or use for carrying things or pulling vehicles.
A common four-legged animal (Felis silvestris) that is often kept as a household pet.
A large cat (Panthera leo) that is native to Africa, Asia and formerly much of Europe.
A large carnivorous animal (Panthera tigris) of the cat family indigenous to Asia.
Of, relating to, or denoting the sex which is generally characterized as the one associated with the larger gametes (for species which have two sexes and for which this distinction can be made).
Relating to the female sex of animals (adjective).
A female animal (Noun)
A cold-blooded vertebrate animal that lives in water that moves with the help of fins and breathes using gills (Pisces).
Any of the black, red, brown, or yellow insects of the family Formicidae characterized by a large head and by living in organized colonies.
A type of domesticated bird from the order of Galliformes which is often raised as a type of poultry (Gallus gallus domesticus).
Insects related to grasshoppers.
A human being, any living member of Homo sapiens.
A class of the Arthropoda typically having a segmented body with an external chitinous covering, a pair of compound eyes, a pair of antennae, three pairs of mouthparts, and two pairs of wings.

Any reptile of the suborder Lacertilia, especially those of the family Lacertidae, typically having an elongated body, four limbs, and a small tail: includes the gechos, iguanas, chameleons, monitors, and slow worms.
A nocturnal, bioluminescent beetle of the family Lampyridae.
One of several small mammals of the family Leporidae, with long ears, long hind legs and a short, fluffy tail.

Relating to the male sex of animals.

A predatory insect of the order Mantodea; mantid; praying mantis.

A common, four-legged animal (Ovis) that is commonly kept by humans for its wool.
A small song bird, in the family Passeridae.
A lepidopteran that is active at day.
A small or medium-sized rodent of the family Sciuridae.
Any reptile of the suborder Serpentes, typically having a scaly cylindrical limbless body, fused eyelids, and a jaw modified for swallowing large prey.

A primate from the group *New World monkeys* or *Old World monkeys* (Simiiformes, excluding the superfamily Hominoidea or apes) that lives mainly in rainforests and is distinguished from an Ape by its smaller size and its tail.
A common, four-legged animal (Sus scrofa) that has cloven hooves, bristles and a nose adapted for digging and is farmed by humans for its meat.
A reptile of the order Testudines (the crown group of the superorder Chelonia), characterised by a special bony or cartilaginous shell developed from their ribs that acts as a shield.
A legendary animal with a horn on the forehead.
A large beast of prey of the family Ursidae, related to the dog and raccoon, having shaggy hair, a very small tail, and flat feet.
